Qualitative activity recognization

-how well the activity is performed?

Anonymous Student

August 19, 2016

Background

Using devices such as Jawbone Up, Nike FuelBand, and Fitbit it is now possible to collect a large amount of data about personal activity relatively inexpensively. One thing that people regularly do is quantify how much of a particular activity they do, but they rarely quantify how well they do it. In this project, our goal will be to use data from accelerometers on the belt, forearm, arm, and dumbell of 6 participants. They were asked to perform barbell lifts correctly and incorrectly in 5 different ways. More information can be found here.

The entire training data set can be downloaded from here. This is the data set I will use to train and test the model. The testing data set downloaded from here is reserved to answer 20 excercise questions later.

# Load training data
# download from "http://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/predmachlearn/pml-training.csv"
data <- read.csv(file = "pml-training.csv",

test20 <- read.csv(file = "pml-testing.csv", 
                     na.strings=c("NA","NaN", " ", "", "#DIV/0!"))

Summary

Adapted from Velloso et al. I used a Random Forest approach to characterized a subset of features, selected in a random and independent manner with the same distribution for each of the trees in the forest. In this project I used 4 random forests and each forest was implemented with 100 trees. To investigate if correlationed features would degrade the performance, I built two models one using all features and one with the high correlated features removed.

Data splitting

I split the data into 60% training and 40% testing.

# set random seed
set.seed(12234)

# split dataframe into training and testing sets
# 60% of total data goes towards training and 40% of the remaining for testing
inTrain <- createDataPartition(y = data$classe, p=0.60, list=FALSE)
training <- data[inTrain, ]
testing <- data[-inTrain, ]

Feature extraction

Only based on the training data set, I remove the features with near zero variance and high correlations. For comparision, I built two models one with the high correlated features removed and one didn’t.

# remove user name and other identify info
metainfo <- training[,1:7]
nzv <- nearZeroVar(training[,-c(1:7)])

# remove near zero variance features
trainExtract <- training[,-c(nzv,1:7)]

# remove features with missing values
trainExtract <- trainExtract[colSums(is.na(trainExtract)) == 0]

# remove features high correlation (>0.75)
par(ps=6)
correlations <- cor(trainExtract[,-length(trainExtract)])
corrplot.mixed(correlations, order = "hclust", tl.col="black", 
                 tl.pos = "lt", lower = "circle", upper = "number")

highCorr <- findCorrelation(correlations, cutoff = .75)
print(highCorr)
##  [1]  9  1  8 15  7 10 28 27 14 16 17 23 33 19 25 39 11
trainExtractNoCorr <- trainExtract[, -highCorr]

# The predictors used without removing high correlated features

Training

I built 4 random forests each with 100 trees. The importance of selected predictors are plotted.

Clearly these two models have not significant differences in accuracy (in-sample-error).

It shows that using all predictors (excluding missing values), the accuracy is 0.9882743 (out-of-sample error 0.0117257 ), comparing with 0.9816467 (out-of-sample error 0.0183533 ) using less correlated predictors. Although no statistically significant difference, the accuracy is slightly higher using all predictors.

Conclusions

The goal of this project is to predict the manner in which they did the exercise. I included upto 40 variables to predict how well each excerice has been performed using 4 random forests each have 100 trees. Cross-validation was performed in eaching training and all predictors were selected randomly. The out-of-sample error for the model including all predictors is 0.0117257. This model will be used to predict 20 different test cases.
